WEBVTT

00:01.102 --> 00:03.836
<i>Crime fighting gets an upgrade</i>
<i>on</i> apb.

00:03.838 --> 00:05.838
- So, are you impressed?
- Wow.

00:05.840 --> 00:08.674
<i>Catch all-new episodes mondays.</i>
<i>And check out our</i>
<i>other fox programs.</i>

00:08.676 --> 00:11.810
Bones, sleepy hollow
<i>and</i> 24: Legacy.

00:11.812 --> 00:14.546
- Why does it need to be you?
- I'm the only one I can trust.

00:14.548 --> 00:15.748
<i>Only on fox.</i>

00:16.951 --> 00:18.450
<i>A Maverick billionaire...</i>

00:18.452 --> 00:20.352
<i>My name is gideon Reeves.</i>

00:20.354 --> 00:24.156
<i>I built an empire making
rockets, computers, robots...</i>

00:24.158 --> 00:26.125
<i>Made over $100 billion.</i>

00:26.127 --> 00:27.226
<i>Know how I did it?</i>

00:27.228 --> 00:29.028
I'm an engineer.

00:29.030 --> 00:30.863
<i>...Touched by tragedy...</i>

00:30.865 --> 00:33.065
The money!
- No!

00:33.067 --> 00:34.666
<i>My friend has been shot!</i>

00:34.668 --> 00:36.535
Where the hell are you people?!

00:36.537 --> 00:39.204
<i>...Takes on the
biggest engineering challenge</i>

00:39.206 --> 00:40.472
<i>of his career...</i>

00:40.474 --> 00:41.874
I want justice
for Elliot James Sully.

00:41.876 --> 00:44.643
Give me the 13th district
to run.

00:44.645 --> 00:47.246
A civilian can't take over
a police district.

00:47.248 --> 00:49.214
They can, with a special
appointment from this committee.

00:49.216 --> 00:52.484
<i>...To revolutionize
a police force...</i>

00:52.486 --> 00:54.553
Technology doesn't
solve cases, cops do.

00:54.555 --> 00:56.155
You haven't met
my technology.

01:00.061 --> 01:01.060
Wow.

01:01.062 --> 01:02.761
<i>...And save a city.</i>

01:02.763 --> 01:05.230
You guys are my partners.

01:05.232 --> 01:06.465
We're gonna change the world.

01:07.601 --> 01:10.069
<i>No, first you make me dinner,</i>

01:10.071 --> 01:12.738
<i>then we get comfortable.</i>

01:12.740 --> 01:15.040
Yeah, I'll be over in a second.

01:15.042 --> 01:16.442
Uh-huh.

01:16.444 --> 01:18.343
Okay. Love you, too.

01:18.345 --> 01:19.912
All right, bye.

02:06.660 --> 02:08.092
The mayor's
office asked me

02:08.095 --> 02:10.662
to do a comprehensive legal
review of all of your cases.

02:10.663 --> 02:12.664
I have to say, I see
a lot of problems there.

02:12.666 --> 02:14.399
No. Check the paper.
Did you mean a lot of success?

02:14.401 --> 02:16.068
Crime is down
across the district.

02:16.070 --> 02:17.269
It's true.

02:17.271 --> 02:18.971
We're down eight percent.
Well, anybody can

02:18.973 --> 02:20.906
generate good numbers
if they want to break the rules.

02:20.908 --> 02:22.774
Break the rules?
How are we br... what?

02:22.776 --> 02:24.009
Did you even consult a lawyer

02:24.011 --> 02:25.744
before you shot a man
with a drone?

02:25.746 --> 02:27.779
Or before you set up
a completely unorthodox

02:27.781 --> 02:28.847
surveillance system?

02:28.849 --> 02:31.283
We're doing things better.

02:31.285 --> 02:33.452
We're making the city safer.

02:33.454 --> 02:35.020
Safer. Oh.

02:35.022 --> 02:37.122
What about the giant
explosion in the middle

02:37.124 --> 02:38.457
of the city last week?

02:38.459 --> 02:39.858
Was that safer?

02:39.860 --> 02:42.161
That's a matter of perspective.

02:42.163 --> 02:43.529
Hmm.
- Look,

02:43.531 --> 02:47.032
we both know that this is
as much about the fact

02:47.034 --> 02:49.668
that your ex-wife works here
than it is about

02:49.670 --> 02:51.703
anything that I'm doing.

02:51.705 --> 02:53.772
My marriage has nothing
to do with this.

02:55.509 --> 02:57.543
This is about your blatant
disregard for the law.

02:57.545 --> 02:59.545
Oh, and, Mr. Reeves,

02:59.547 --> 03:02.047
I'll see you at the
mayor's office on Thursday.

03:02.049 --> 03:04.783
We'll determine which of
those cases will be dismissed.

03:04.785 --> 03:06.885
I suggest you come prepared.

03:10.324 --> 03:12.958
Oh, you've stepped
in it now.

03:14.728 --> 03:16.228
I just... oh, my...

03:16.230 --> 03:17.663
This is...

03:17.665 --> 03:19.298
They're seriously
gonna let bad guys go

03:19.300 --> 03:20.566
for the sake of politics?

03:22.703 --> 03:25.704
You embarrassed the mayor
when you took over the district.

03:25.706 --> 03:27.339
He wants payback.

03:27.341 --> 03:30.008
I've been around a long time,
and I'm telling you

03:30.010 --> 03:32.411
there's only one way out
of a situation like this.

03:32.413 --> 03:33.845
Is it a killer robot?

03:33.847 --> 03:36.081
Tell me it's a killer robot.
I'll build one.

03:36.083 --> 03:38.650
No. Bottom line is,
we need a win.

03:38.652 --> 03:41.720
Something big enough
that the Asa and the mayor

03:41.722 --> 03:44.790
can't take the political hit
and use it against us.

03:54.868 --> 03:56.935
Yeah, he didn't
take anything.

03:56.937 --> 03:59.905
Seems crazy. I mean, what's
a guy like that thinking?

03:59.907 --> 04:02.574
Yo, gideon, we
need your help.

04:02.576 --> 04:05.077
Boy, if I had a dollar
for every time I heard that,

04:05.079 --> 04:06.945
I'd be a... oh, that's right.
I already am.

04:06.947 --> 04:08.847
Got a case that
came in last night.

04:08.849 --> 04:10.215
A weird one.
- Yeah.

04:10.217 --> 04:13.885
Some nutjob shot up an atm
last night about 8:00.

04:13.887 --> 04:15.454
Alarm goes off, we respond.

04:15.456 --> 04:16.688
He's just standing there,

04:16.690 --> 04:20.024
waiting, gun on
the ground, hands up.

04:20.027 --> 04:22.127
All right,
don't take this the wrong way.

04:22.129 --> 04:24.062
Sounds like a case
where you <i> don't</i> need my help.

04:24.064 --> 04:26.231
- I think he did it.
- Yeah, we got that.

04:26.233 --> 04:29.534
The thing is, he says he was
trying to get our attention,

04:29.536 --> 04:31.370
'cause he needs to talk to you.

04:31.372 --> 04:33.372
He made
over 50 apb calls,

04:33.374 --> 04:34.706
but they all got dispatched
to the 21st district.

04:34.708 --> 04:36.642
They ignored 'em.
He called here

04:36.644 --> 04:39.778
a bunch, too, but the desk
wouldn't connect him.

04:39.780 --> 04:41.113
Guess he figured
committing a crime

04:41.115 --> 04:43.015
in the 13th was
the only way.

04:49.723 --> 04:51.723
Mr. Reeves.

04:51.725 --> 04:53.158
Thanks for coming.

04:53.160 --> 04:54.826
Hello.

04:54.828 --> 04:56.395
Mr. Reeves, you've been
an inspiration to me.

04:56.397 --> 04:57.396
Oh.

04:57.398 --> 04:59.431
Um...

04:59.433 --> 05:01.466
An inspiration to shoot an atm?

05:02.903 --> 05:06.772
Yeah, I'm, uh... I'm sorry
about that. I just, um...

05:06.774 --> 05:08.573
I just didn't
know what to do.
- Okay.

05:08.575 --> 05:11.943
Then why exactly
did you need to talk to me?

05:11.945 --> 05:15.647
Well, it's my daughter, Maya.

05:15.649 --> 05:19.318
She was a student
at the university of Chicago.

05:19.320 --> 05:22.154
And last year, she started
to experiment with drugs.

05:22.156 --> 05:24.189
And we tried
to intervene,

05:24.191 --> 05:26.191
but, uh, she
had a stroke.

05:26.193 --> 05:27.793
She survived,

05:27.795 --> 05:29.928
but she's just, um...

05:29.930 --> 05:32.030
She's learning
how to talk again.

05:32.032 --> 05:34.766
I'm so sorry. Um, uh...

05:34.768 --> 05:36.702
I still don't understand,
though. Why...

05:36.704 --> 05:38.770
I just felt like I
had to do something.

05:38.772 --> 05:40.439
Right?

05:40.441 --> 05:42.374
She o.D.'D on a drug
called hi-town.

05:42.376 --> 05:45.310
It's a synthetic heroin
and methamphetamine.

05:45.312 --> 05:47.713
The doctors said that
that particular combination

05:47.715 --> 05:50.182
causes accidental overdoses
all the time.

05:50.184 --> 05:51.483
Yeah, it's true.

05:51.485 --> 05:53.352
The meth keeps the kids up
and doing more.

05:53.354 --> 05:56.221
The opiates kick in,
knocks 'em to their knees,

05:56.223 --> 05:58.657
but no one's sure who deals it.
And that's what I
wanted to find out.

05:58.659 --> 06:01.793
I want to stop the guy who
gave this drug to my daughter

06:01.795 --> 06:04.563
before he hurts
someone else's kid.

06:04.565 --> 06:07.332
And then I saw what you
did for your friend,

06:07.334 --> 06:09.501
and how you
found his killer.

06:09.503 --> 06:11.570
I went to mit, too.

06:11.572 --> 06:13.905
Class of '90.

06:13.907 --> 06:16.174
I don't know. I
guess I just, um...

06:16.176 --> 06:18.176
Wanted to do the same thing.

06:18.178 --> 06:20.412
Yeah. I'm not quite
the engineer you are,

06:20.414 --> 06:22.481
certainly not
a billionaire.

06:22.483 --> 06:24.716
All I got for my
trouble was a-a beating

06:24.718 --> 06:26.551
from some
street dealers.

06:26.553 --> 06:28.987
Look, I know I'm gonna go to
prison for what I did yesterday.

06:28.989 --> 06:31.823
I'm okay with that,
but I, um, uh...

06:31.825 --> 06:34.259
I'm asking you, please,
just-just go to my home.

06:34.261 --> 06:37.996
I've got files.
I've got evidence.

06:37.998 --> 06:41.566
Just please,
just take a look.

06:44.171 --> 06:46.605
Rookie, you write
this many moving violations,

06:46.607 --> 06:49.074
I'll give you
a police medal myself.

06:49.076 --> 06:51.443
Don't. Don't
encourage him, Bernie.

06:51.445 --> 06:52.844
Come on.
What was that?

06:52.846 --> 06:55.113
What was what? I was
getting us ticket books.

06:55.115 --> 06:57.716
You take four,
they expect you to fill four.

06:57.718 --> 06:59.351
Cobb! Reyes!

06:59.353 --> 07:00.919
Yeah.

07:00.921 --> 07:02.854
What beat are you guys
working today?

07:02.856 --> 07:04.122
Uh, we're on
a traffic car.

07:04.124 --> 07:05.624
I have a special
assignment for you.

07:05.626 --> 07:07.526
Our tact team's been
running down some leads

07:07.528 --> 07:10.028
on possible fugitives
in the district.

07:10.030 --> 07:11.630
What do you need us for?

07:11.632 --> 07:13.298
Ada here's got a new way
to skin the cat.

07:13.300 --> 07:15.400
So I programmed a way to cross-
check records and find people

07:15.402 --> 07:17.569
who've been changing aliases to
stay out of federal databases.

07:17.571 --> 07:18.537
Okay.

07:18.539 --> 07:20.138
Well, which means what?

07:21.375 --> 07:23.442
Probable fugitives.
We got a hit in the district,

07:23.444 --> 07:25.811
a Reggie Walker
on 51st and damen.

07:25.813 --> 07:28.747
According to our records,
he's only existed for

07:28.749 --> 07:30.315
the past seven years.

07:30.317 --> 07:32.984
I'm gonna send his info
to your squad car now.

07:32.986 --> 07:34.286
He dangerous?

07:34.288 --> 07:36.321
Yeah, there a chance
this guy eats people or what?

07:36.323 --> 07:39.391
He's not hiding from the FBI
because he's an angel.

07:39.393 --> 07:40.926
Look, I'm gonna level with you.

07:40.928 --> 07:43.328
The district could use
a little good publicity.

07:43.330 --> 07:44.729
You guys reel in a big fish,

07:44.731 --> 07:46.264
it gives the mayor
something to brag about

07:46.266 --> 07:48.600
and leave us all alone.
- Okay.

07:48.602 --> 07:50.335
But if the guy turns out
to be a cannibal,

07:50.337 --> 07:51.570
I'm feeding him
the rookie here first.

07:57.444 --> 07:59.511
<i>Thank you for coming.</i>

07:59.513 --> 08:01.480
I'm so sorry for any
trouble Robert caused.

08:01.482 --> 08:03.515
He didn't tell me what
he was going to do.
Oh, that's all right.

08:03.517 --> 08:06.117
We've all wanted
to shoot an atm at some point.

08:06.119 --> 08:07.819
Is this everything?

08:07.821 --> 08:09.688
Um, I think so, yes.

08:09.690 --> 08:12.357
It was all printed out and
organized just in case you came.

08:12.359 --> 08:15.927
I have to ask... was your husband
ever violent before this?

08:15.929 --> 08:18.363
Oh, God, no. Robert...

08:18.365 --> 08:21.099
He was always in his head,
always inventing things,

08:21.101 --> 08:24.035
and fiddling around on
his computer, and, well...

08:24.037 --> 08:26.638
And the apple didn't
fall far from the tree.

08:26.640 --> 08:28.340
Those are all of Maya's
science fair awards.

08:30.844 --> 08:33.477
We were both so proud. I...

08:33.480 --> 08:36.313
The man who gave
her those drugs...

08:36.316 --> 08:37.549
He broke our
little girl.

08:39.385 --> 08:40.719
Since the stroke,

08:40.721 --> 08:42.153
she hasn't said a word.

08:42.155 --> 08:43.355
I just don't know

08:43.357 --> 08:45.223
how it all went so wrong.

08:45.225 --> 08:47.492
Well...

08:47.494 --> 08:50.195
That's exactly what
we're gonna try to figure out.

08:57.371 --> 08:59.571
<i>Let me just get this straight.</i>

08:59.573 --> 09:01.973
You want to take on
a shot-in-the-dark drug case

09:01.975 --> 09:04.209
for a vigilante now?

09:04.211 --> 09:07.045
Well, there might be
more positive ways of put...

09:07.047 --> 09:08.413
Yeah, that sounds about right.

09:08.415 --> 09:11.149
Look, we found
some evidence from Mr. ruiz.

09:11.151 --> 09:12.584
Not a lot, but he did find

09:12.586 --> 09:14.085
the major points of sale
for hi-town.

09:14.087 --> 09:15.253
I mean, it's a start.

09:15.255 --> 09:17.923
A start? Remember our talk about

09:17.925 --> 09:20.091
doing something to make
us popular at city hall?

09:20.093 --> 09:21.493
Any of that ring a bell?

09:21.495 --> 09:25.230
That sounds familiar, yes,
but this...

09:25.232 --> 09:26.598
People are dying, captain.

09:26.600 --> 09:28.767
This hi-town stuff...
It's poison.

09:28.769 --> 09:30.535
I know that. But Murphy,

09:30.537 --> 09:33.838
you know that trying to hit
a major drug dealer is tough

09:33.840 --> 09:35.273
under the best

09:35.275 --> 09:36.942
of circumstances,
and this is

09:36.944 --> 09:38.944
far from the best circumstances.

09:38.946 --> 09:40.779
Didn't jfk say something

09:40.781 --> 09:42.948
about doing things
because they're hard?

09:42.950 --> 09:44.849
And it didn't end well for him,
either, as I recall.

09:44.851 --> 09:47.452
I said we needed a win,
not an uphill battle.

09:47.454 --> 09:49.621
But how hard can it be?

09:49.623 --> 09:50.956
They're selling the stuff.

09:50.958 --> 09:52.424
Someone has money,
someone has drugs.

09:52.426 --> 09:53.625
They trade the money
for the drugs, and then

09:53.627 --> 09:55.293
we catch somebody,
and then we work our way up.

09:55.295 --> 09:57.128
Oh.

09:57.130 --> 09:58.730
Is that all there is to it?

09:58.732 --> 10:00.732
Murphy, maybe you should

10:00.734 --> 10:04.035
give Mr. Reeves here a little
lesson in the local drug trade.

10:04.037 --> 10:05.837
I'm on it, captain.

10:13.747 --> 10:15.747
<i>Seriously, I don't see</i>

10:15.749 --> 10:17.282
why this is necessary.

10:17.284 --> 10:19.818
I know. That's
why we're here.

10:19.820 --> 10:22.220
What are we even
looking for, urban blight?

10:22.222 --> 10:23.455
Yeah, I-I see it.

10:23.457 --> 10:24.756
It's-it's an American tragedy.

10:24.758 --> 10:27.292
Can you just shut up?

10:27.294 --> 10:28.627
All right, right there.

10:28.629 --> 10:29.761
That car...

10:29.763 --> 10:32.130
That's the buyer.

10:32.132 --> 10:33.398
How can you tell?

10:33.400 --> 10:34.933
'Cause she's not driving
five Miles an hour

10:34.935 --> 10:37.335
just to take in the
beautiful scenery.

10:37.337 --> 10:38.670
Okay, that guy...
He's the lookout.

10:38.672 --> 10:40.305
<i>He watches out for the cops.</i>

10:40.307 --> 10:42.173
And that one
right there...

10:42.175 --> 10:44.275
He steers the buyer
to the banker.

10:45.278 --> 10:47.145
That's the banker?

10:47.147 --> 10:50.448
<i>That's quite a title for a guy
with such ill-fitting pants.</i>

10:50.450 --> 10:52.817
<i>The banker never touches
the drugs, just the money.</i>

10:53.820 --> 10:55.887
That's the slinger.

10:57.691 --> 10:59.557
He handles the drugs.

11:03.664 --> 11:05.664
What is he, 12?

11:05.666 --> 11:07.265
Probably younger.

11:07.267 --> 11:09.601
Okay. So now who
do you arrest?

11:09.603 --> 11:12.303
The banker for taking cash
from a guy at a car?

11:12.305 --> 11:13.972
Or the little kid with
$30 worth of drugs?

11:13.974 --> 11:15.473
Well, there has
to be more drugs.

11:15.475 --> 11:17.008
Sure, under a rock
somewhere in this lot.

11:17.010 --> 11:18.677
Even if you do
manage an arrest,

11:18.679 --> 11:21.046
good luck getting any
of these guys to talk.

11:21.048 --> 11:23.181
Those guys aren't afraid
of jail. They're planning on it.

11:23.183 --> 11:25.517
There has to be some connection
to the higher-ups,

11:25.519 --> 11:26.885
some way...
They're not here.

11:26.887 --> 11:28.486
They're at home,
counting their cash.

11:32.059 --> 11:33.725
But they do touch the cash.

11:33.727 --> 11:37.095
Yeah. But, I mean, good luck
trying to trace it back to them.

11:39.232 --> 11:41.066
All right, challenge accepted.

11:46.339 --> 11:50.008
Says here Mr. Reggie Walker
lives in number 2.

11:50.010 --> 11:51.810
Sounds about right.

11:51.812 --> 11:54.579
So we really don't have
any idea what this guy did?

11:54.581 --> 11:56.581
No. Just that he's living
under a fake name.

11:56.583 --> 11:58.883
The idea is we're gonna
find the guy, talk to him,

11:58.885 --> 12:00.151
find out what he's done.

12:00.153 --> 12:02.087
Or we'll just find out
that the guy's got

12:02.089 --> 12:03.421
a typo on his driver's license.

12:03.423 --> 12:05.757
I don't know.
Looks pretty official to me.

12:05.759 --> 12:08.526
Yeah. So did the warrant
that I had to serve

12:08.528 --> 12:11.496
on a six-year-old last year
for reckless driving.

12:11.498 --> 12:13.898
Trust me, nothing screws
up like a computer.

12:13.900 --> 12:15.700
We're not gonna find
any bad guys.

12:15.702 --> 12:17.268
Mr. Walker!

12:18.872 --> 12:21.372
Reggie Walker! Cpd!

12:21.374 --> 12:23.374
We got a workplace listed.
We could check that out.

12:23.376 --> 12:24.943
Shut up.
Hey, just 'cause I'm new...

12:24.945 --> 12:25.944
No, shut up.

12:25.946 --> 12:27.078
Do you hear that?

12:33.553 --> 12:34.619
No! Stop!

12:34.621 --> 12:35.620
Stop!

12:35.622 --> 12:36.755
Police!

12:37.290 --> 12:38.556
1312 emergency.

12:38.558 --> 12:40.391
Black male, white t-shirt,
blue jeans,

12:40.393 --> 12:41.626
heading southbound
on damen.

12:44.097 --> 12:46.064
Suspect is crossing 51st!

13:00.147 --> 13:04.149
1312, uh, we lost him
down the alley by 52nd.

13:05.152 --> 13:07.385
Sure looked like
a bad guy to me.

13:08.922 --> 13:10.822
I've been going through the
stuff that we got from ruiz.

13:10.824 --> 13:12.824
He's been able to ID some
of the smaller dealers,

13:12.826 --> 13:15.059
but there's nothing we can
really build a case on.

13:15.061 --> 13:16.561
Well, as long as we know
who's selling,

13:16.563 --> 13:18.830
I think we're
in business.

13:18.832 --> 13:22.333
So you said the higher-ups
aren't touching the drugs,

13:22.335 --> 13:24.169
but the cash finds
its way to them.

13:24.171 --> 13:25.170
Yeah, but, I mean...

13:25.172 --> 13:26.671
All right, Pete,
show her the money.

13:26.673 --> 13:28.339
Mm-hmm.

13:28.341 --> 13:31.676
So, the idea...

13:31.678 --> 13:35.113
Is to dust each bill

